## Phase 3 — Report

The worker commits source (`keeper commit-work`) before stamping `keeper plan done`, and self-checks its own delivery cleanliness (its session files committed) before returning — so a `done` verdict in Phase 2b means both commits landed and nothing of the worker's is left dirty. The orchestrator never commits source, never runs `keeper plan done`, and never inspects git porcelain.

**Do NOT close the epic** — the orchestrator never closes; closing is a separate automated step. **`keeper commit-work` failures surface as BLOCKED** — a lint/commit/push failure makes the worker return `BLOCKED: TOOLING_FAILURE` with the verbatim envelope (Phase 2b's BLOCKED short-circuit catches it); the resume path picks up via the non-`done` verdict.

One-line summary, using `reconcile`'s `epic_progress` and the worker's returned commit sha:

> `fn-1-foo.3` done. commit: `<sha>`. epic progress: M/N tasks done.

Include the per-task commit sha from the worker return and `epic_progress.done` / `epic_progress.total` from the final `reconcile` envelope. No menu, no follow-up prompts.

